\par }\pard \s15\qc {\fs32 Porting a Windows Application to OS/2}
\par \pard \s15 
\par The major steps required to port the sample Windows application to OS/2 using DAPIE are:
\par 
\par \pard\plain \s18\li576 \f4\cf1 {\field{\*\fldinst SYMBOL 117 \\f "Wingdings" \\s 12 \\h}{\fldrslt }}Convert the Windows 32-bit resource file {\b sample.rc} to an OS/2 resource file using SMART (SMARTRC).
\par {\field{\*\fldinst SYMBOL 117 \\f "Wingdings" \\s 12 \\h}{\fldrslt }}Convert the Windows help file {\b sample.rtf} to an OS/2 IPF file using SMART (SMARTHLP)
\par {\field{\*\fldinst SYMBOL 117 \\f "Wingdings" \\s 12 \\h}{\fldrslt }}Copy the lines that SMART generated in {\b sample.hhh} to sample.h.
\par {\field{\*\fldinst SYMBOL 117 \\f "Wingdings" \\s 12 \\h}{\fldrslt }}Change the line in sample.c{\b :\line \tab #include <windows.h>\line }to:\line \tab {\b #include <os2win.h>}
\par {\field{\*\fldinst SYMBOL 117 \\f "Wingdings" \\s 12 \\h}{\fldrslt }}Change the code in {\b sample.c} that uses string resource IDs to use MAKEINTRESOURCE with the numeric IDs that SMART generated in {\b sample.hhh}.
\par {\field{\*\fldinst SYMBOL 117 \\f "Wingdings" \\s 12 \\h}{\fldrslt }}Create a DEF file for the executable {\b sample.exe.}
\par {\field{\*\fldinst SYMBOL 117 \\f "Wingdings" \\s 12 \\h}{\fldrslt }}Create a new {\b makefile} the project.
