\par {\fs32 Issues Involved in Creating a Mixed-mode DAPIE Application}
\par 
\par \pard \s15 There are several major issues a developer must keep in mind when producing a mixed-mode DAPIE - native PM application:
\par 
\par \pard\plain \s18\li576 \f4\cf1 {\field{\*\fldinst SYMBOL 117 \\f "Wingdings" \\s 12 \\h}{\fldrslt }}PM native code should be kept in separate source files from DAPIE code.
\par {\field{\*\fldinst SYMBOL 117 \\f "Wingdings" \\s 12 \\h}{\fldrslt }}The window handle of a top-level DAPIE window is actually a frame window handle.
\par {\field{\*\fldinst SYMBOL 117 \\f "Wingdings" \\s 12 \\h}{\fldrslt }}Every top-level DAPIE window has a client window that is transparent to DAPIE APIs; this includes dialogs.
\par {\field{\*\fldinst SYMBOL 117 \\f "Wingdings" \\s 12 \\h}{\fldrslt }}DAPIE and PM window handles are generally interchangeable.
\par {\field{\*\fldinst SYMBOL 117 \\f "Wingdings" \\s 12 \\h}{\fldrslt }}DAPIE HDCs should not be used with Gpi calls and PM HPSs and HDCs should not be used with DAPIE APIs.
\par {\field{\*\fldinst SYMBOL 117 \\f "Wingdings" \\s 12 \\h}{\fldrslt }}DAPIE kernel handles are not compatible with OS/2 base handles (e.g. file handles).
\par }